[Student "S"]
{With 17 points and a balanced hand you naturally open 1NT. South overcalls 2\S. Your partner then bids 2NT.  

Your partner invited you to bid 3NT if you had 17 points, and you have 17 points. You trust your partner so you bid 3NT.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \SQ.

<b>East plays 3NT. South leads the \SQ.</b>

Winner count: \S 2 : \H 0 : \D 0 : \C 2 : Total = 4

This looks scary. Needing 5 more tricks means you are going to have to establish <b>BOTH</b> red suits. And with only two \S stoppers you have to hope South doesn't have both red Aces. If he does, you're down, so just assume that he only has one of them. Now if you can just figure out which Ace South has you can establish that suit first.

But you don't have to guess, there is a better way. South overcalled at the 2-level with a Queen-high suit and one outside Ace. THAT is bold. Surely he has at least a 6-card suit to justify that overcall. If so, then a simple hold-up will be worthwhile. So you let South hold the first trick, and when he leads another \S you win the \SK in your hand. If South has a 6-card suit North is now void of \Ss.

Play \Ds to drive out the \DA. If North has it he will not have another \S to force you with. If South has it he can force out your last \S, but then won't have the \HA for an entry. However the Aces are split - as long as South doesn't have both - you will establish 9 tricks.

Without the holdup you could still have made the contract, but only if you had established the \H winners first. That would have been a total guess.

With the holdup it didn't matter which red suit you established first.}
[Play "W"]SQ

