[Student "S"]
{You really really want to say 3\S. Here are three good reasons you shouldn't.

You have 9 \Hs between you. You may have only 7 \Ss. If you bid 3\S partner may bid again. You haven't been doubled.

East would play 3\H.

Click 

West plays 3\H. North leads the \SQ.

<b>West plays 3\H. North leads the \SQ.</b>

It turns out there was a fourth reason not to bid 3\S - the opponents might lead the suit.

Losers: \S 0 : \H 1/2 : \D 1 : \C 4 : Total = 6/7

The \S lead is about the best thing that could have happened to you. You win with dummy's \SA and play \SK, discarding your \D. You then lead a small \C, covering anything South plays. You'd like to ruff a \C if you can, but if they play trumps to stop you then you'd like the trump play to come from North. North leads the \H3, South plays the \HK, and you win with the \HA. You play a small \C. If the defender who wins the \C doesn't play another trump then you can ruff your third \C in dummy. If the defender <b>DOES</b> play a trump, then you lose only one trump trick. You end up going down 1, which is pretty good.

Some contracts are impossible. So you just play to keep the damage as low as possible.}
[Play "W"]SQ

