[Student "S"]
{With 19 points and a 5-card \H suit you open 1\H.

Partner raises you to 2\H.  

Partner's bid shows 6-10 points. If he has 6 it might be close, but otherwise you should have a game. You bid 4\H.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \SQ.

<b>East plays 4\H. South leads the \SQ.</b>

Losers: \S 2 : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 2 : Total = 5

The three minor suit losers cannot be avoided, but the two \S losers can be ruffed in dummy. A small amount of caution is in order. Win the \SK and play the \SA. Ruff a \S with dummy's \H8. North shows out but cannot over-ruff. Return to your hand with the \DA and ruff your last \S with dummy's \HA. Return to your hand with a trump. You will lose three minor suit cards and nothing else.

Some would go down on this hand when they ruffed the first \S with dummy's \H3 and North over-ruffed. It is pretty clear that you should ruff with one of the higher cards, but sometimes the thought comes too late.}
[Play "W"]SQ

